  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3196" xml:lang="fr">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <opener>Mon cher M<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi> le D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi> Schuchardt,</opener>

        <p>vous ne me donnez pas le rang de Bascologue mais seulement de Bascophile! My Bascologizing in which I am like a pelican in the wilderness all alone sometimes fills my head with strange fancies - I now derive Horatius from <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">hora</hi> a dog with the termination <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">tto</hi> or<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none"> ti</hi> (eguiati = verax) &amp; a latin case-ending. A cloud is a covering: may then Slovenian <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">odéja</hi> = “decke” be Basque? I have seen in no Dictionary (I have not access here to Aizkibel or <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5695">Larramendi</persName>) the word <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">gortcen, gortu</hi> used in the Souletin imitation to translate “accendere” in flame (the heart) - I find in Slovenian <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">oséba</hi> = “Person”. it means “<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">uncle</hi>” in Basque. I have heard that priests are called “uncle” in parts of Austria, and <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">
Persona</hi> both in the French and English church was applied to the curé of a parish or the canon of a Cathedral. I find in Anglo Saxon <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">aelc</hi> in Low German <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">
elk</hi> in old English <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">elch</hi> = modern English <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">each</hi>. These words remind me of Basque <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">elkar</hi> which means “each other” “each reciprocally”. I like <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5524">
Leiçarragas</persName>
          <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">beçalacatu</hi> = “to make like unto” – almost “<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">quasificare</hi>” or “<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">similificare</hi>” and the S. I. <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">yakintsutzen</hi> “to make wise”. I have returned to <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1294">De Charencey</persName> the 2<hi
            rendition="#sup">nd</hi> proofs of my Concordance to S<hi
            rendition="#sup">t</hi> John of which he is about to publish the first 3<hi
            rendition="#sup">rd</hi> or half. In the preface I announce that your work, on the Basque verb is soon to appear. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2445">Priebsch</persName> is not well &amp; is going to Oxford at the end of the month. Have you read Lancianis books on Roman archeology? For the last 5 months I have lost M<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>
          <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5682">D’Abbadies</persName> friendship I hear someone has filled him with <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
préventions</hi> contre moi - It vexes me very much.</p>
        <p>
          <note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der linken Seite.</note>
          <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1062">
Azkue</persName> says my labours on Basque will be recognised by posterity!</p>
        <closer>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">E. S. Dodgson.</persName>
          </signed>
          <dateline>9 Fév: 1893. Paris.</dateline>
        </closer>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
      </div>
